I loathe small talk yet I love big talk. Start with traffic and weather and I go into snooze mode because I want to know YOU and when we talk about the sun and the rain and Highway 101, we will probably never get anywhere.

But this week I learned a valuable lesson and I wanted to share it with you. 

I was with an old friend asking an assortment of big talk questions because I felt pressure to make the two hours we had together meaningful. It might be another 10 years before we crossed paths in the same city again, I thought, so I better maximize our time. 

But the opposite happened. I inadvertently pushed her away; my big talk questions overwhelmed her. Two times in a row she answered my question with “I hate being asked that.” Once was acceptable, but the second time it was my fault for not reading her cues. Here I was trying to get to the heart of the matter, her heart, and I was closing it instead. 

I have always hosted shows - a radio show, my online talk show, and now a podcast, and I pride myself on asking deep questions. But on my shows, I intentionally start softer and lead up to the bigger questions. Here I was rushing the process of connection and I failed. Connection comes at a natural pace and I was fighting that.

With big talk and big connecton comes responsibility and trust. The next time I dig towards a friend’s heart, I will do it a bit more thoughtfully and I won’t race the clock to make it happen.

Many of you are new here so I thought I would reintroduce myself! I am a personal branding expert turned author and work life /future of work thinker and entrepreneur. I know this is dizzying; here’s how it all happened.

1. I went to college as a recruited athlete and then returned to earn my MBA. I turned my passion for storytelling into a business by starting the first ever personal branding agency which represented chefs and CEOs and even amazing business icon Lillian Vernon!) 

2. I launched a bestselling book series with Random House called The Experts’ Guides featuring chapters written by luminaries from Barbara Corcoran to Al Roker and Richard Branson. One of them was a dude named Gary Vaynerchuk and together we launched an online talk show that I hosted called Obsessed TV. We produced 75 episodes. 

3. I searched for a work/life balance expert to guide my clients and there wasn’t one, so I became one.

4. I then put my work/life philosophy into my fifth book, The Pie Life and appeared on hundreds of shows and stages talking about work/life, and I hosted a nationally syndicated call-in radio show, but I remained unable to help the women who had left the workforce and couldn’t find their way back — many became stuck selling for multi level marketing  companies. 98% of these women were losing money, not even breaking even. 

5. I wanted to create a tangible opportunity for achieving financial independence. I started a company to train freelancers (for free!) to sell financial services so that they could earn recurring revenue from helping their local businesses. Park Place Payments was born four years ago. Along the way I teamed up with entrepreneur Amy Nelson to launch an iHeart podcast. Each episode of What’s Her Story features one exceptional woman from Abby Wambach to Melinda Gates and Soledad O’Brien. 

Saving the best for last, I am a very proud mom of three amazing kids and trying my best every day to be a great parent. So in addition to talking about work trends, you will hear me saying a lot about parenting - my mistakes, my triumphs, and everything in between. 

Enough about me, please introduce yourself or say hi in the comments! xoSam

For many years I hosted a call in radio show and each week people would call me with their problems. The number one problem people had? They felt stuck - in their careers, in their relationships, their parenting styles, their communities. They felt helpless and unable to see their next move without envisioning a seismic and seemingly impossible change. The amazing thing is that it doesn’t take much to get unstuck. If you are in mud, it is that first step that makes it possible to get out of it. Life is like that too - in every area of our lives it is one small step - asking for a new assignment, adding a weekly date night, taking a daily walk, starting a book club, saying yes to the unlikely invitation.  It begins with one step and realizing that you are the author of your story, the captain of your ship, the painter of your future picture.

My dad is 89 today and though his body is weak, his mind is as strong as ever. 

I used to say that I had the least connected father. Born in Bensonhurst, Brooklyn, Frank Ettus shared a room with his grandmother from birth through college until he entered the navy. He then landed in market research and built a career there. 

But what he lacked in connections, he made up for in spades by believing in me before I could even believe in myself. 

I remember reaching for some crazy internship in college and when he heard I applied he said “of course you will get it.” I didn’t get that one, but his unstoppable belief in me propelled my belief in myself. I always applied and went for it. 

And that impact was more long lasting than any connections. It has informed so much of my parenting today. Our kids are born with the wings and our job as parents is to provide the wind. 

Happy Birthday Dad! Thanks for the love and the wind.

And when it comes to business, the biggest and best chances you can take involve cold outreachesI But you have to do it smartly. Years ago I was featured in an Inc. Magazine article on my techniques. Here is some of what I shared:

Once Ettus has a potential client in her sights, she hunts down all the information she can find -- career history, memberships and professional affiliations, any awards the person may have won. As soon as she understands who she's dealing with, she crafts, but does not send, a personalized e-mail outlining what her firm has to offer. Then she makes the call. NYC with Ella and Barbie.

My feelings about Barbie are complicated. When my girls were toddlers, Barbie was banned from our home. She had perpetuated unrealistic and Eurocentric standards of beauty for decades, and I felt she had no place in our quest to raise strong girls. 

But cut to now, more than 15 years later, and I had to see what the film craze was all about. Through the brilliant script and directing, Greta Gerwig and team artfully turned everything we thought and felt about Barbie on its head. And the broader commentary on gender was genius. I could never have imagined that the doll I resented could headline a movie powerful enough to diminish my past concerns about princess culture and achingly slow progress towards equality. The box office success of such a powerful feminist movie gives me so much hope.

It's also made me look back on the almost 18 years since I began raising kids. So much has changed. And it feels like we are headed in the right direction when it comes to gender and feelings and even ambition. Our kids now have stronger role models, expanded language, and broader opportunities. So, Barbie movie, thanks for inspiring hope and optimism, and for reminding us that we are all capable of immense change.
